One thing is certain: these new rules will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for conducting the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have promulgated new laws that make the process of registration or registration difficult.
This phenomenon has gained in importance after the November 2010 elections, with 675 new republican representatives recorded in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, limiting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as voters on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court file is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state asked voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to raise such a demand.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the last two years, they have promoted draft laws in 34 states that force voters to present a photo ID.
