In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators promoted laws in eight states that abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the voter registration campaigns at the 2004 general elections helped to register some 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the share of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early vote.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although they make up only 13% of the state's voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
By contrast, the whites, representing 76% of the voters, accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
