The Higgs boson analyzes
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused a certain sensation last summer, and for good reason.
It is indeed believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
Finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data are still missing to be completely certain about it.
Nevertheless, let us assume that it is actually the Higgs, since there seems to be a small risk of being deceived, and let us look at what it is about.
There is an inevitably inevitable law in this world that makes two objects not simultaneously present in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try too hard as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli's exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantity state", whereby this "state" consists largely of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons, a nasty gang of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred - in any case not this principle, which means that in fact they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure from the Berkeley laboratories (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing): the mesons, which we will not treat here and the "force particles", through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
But it must be stressed here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle" which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly in this place, like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbing" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More Stable Field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" in order for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be shattered by a very large rock.
That's why a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the fridge by itself.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon) have no mass.
For what can all these researches be "good", asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they are used to check the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to examine all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM in detail.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It has to be said that the latter still has major deficiencies, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (renews ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN until now.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be none.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous stroke laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was initially regarded as a "laboratory play".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras around the world and awarded him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you really never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
With its Committee on Death in Dignity, Quebec has recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate will have to be resumed shortly, even though a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in Victor-Gadbois' palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its work: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he consents to be helped with food.
He even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at Victor-Gadbois' home.
Returning to childhood is unacceptable humiliation for certain persons.
"That depends on the person's ability to take a step backwards," he notes.
For according to several people who work in palliative care, great events take place in the midst of these regressions.
Patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Home are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who take care of them no longer heap them with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and through suffocation".
But the illness really brought me to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she says before accepting that she should be put on a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days she still expects a last visit of her son, who comes from Italy.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers offer personal care and food support.
Palliative care is used when there are no other possibilities.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little if you take into account that one day we'll all die.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given a mouth care with brandy or pepsi as desired.
Diabetic patients no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," reports Nursing Director Nathalie Savard.
Victor-Gadbois home is not a day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years, who enjoys the last family reunion in the yard and is well supported by his pillows as one toasts in his honor, a young man of 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel, concerned.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadboi's home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Domestic Palliative Care in Greater Montreal, are more or less exclusively specializing in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec's health care that causes a number of palliative care specialists to look forward to the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide with concern.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent figures in palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health system is not efficient enough to ensure that all have the right to quality palliative care before they are accepted to go to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room with great pain for 14 days without taking measures to relieve her.
I'm afraid that the only reason patients want to die is because they don't get adequate healthcare.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients bitterly until the last day despite the worst predictions.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued an arduous chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop treatment, she told me she was sorry that I gave up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not allowing this request after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care for the Montreal community, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which means that the patient should be put to sleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly be able to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated, all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be eased."
