A constitution with the crowbar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever with regard to the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power of attorney, it has decided to put everything on one card.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this assembly two additional months to complete its work.
Egypt has now been based on a preliminary text, which has been amended several times for almost two years, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocrat delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "footstep the right."
His supporters are assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text to the Egyptians section by section.
It is also a way for the President to regain his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest is raging all over the country.
After confirming in an interview with American weekly Time, Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote favourably.
Especially since the Egyptian people, with this recourse to a hasty vote, will be given an ultimatum: "You will either vote for my draft or I will retain unlimited authority", the latter should supposedly end after adoption of the Constitution.
85 largely Islamist members of this constituent assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals have not complied with the call.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they believe that they have not been able to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities and civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that most of the articles were adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed at the time of prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the Constituent Assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Finally, Article 2, which attracted all attention, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of justice".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made it possible to apply it more strictly.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"Holiness" responds to the liberals, who regard this as a propaganda blow.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar a consultative function, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying, since "the people who are asked to give an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
One can see here the first signs of a theocracy".
Liberal fears are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be much less moderate than the current one.
"Currently, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, that "as regards Article 220, there may be ambiguity, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, footnote].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide on it."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue: the powers of the army.
In line with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as requested by the associations for the defence of human rights.
The latter also share their fears about the text, which they regard as threatening freedom.
The blasphemy situation is being maintained and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on TV last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel Ukrainian tourists await sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and an untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons for visiting Israel.
bow before the holy places
Visit the river Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding celebration, the walking on the water, the breastfeeding of the sea storm and fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
However, most of the sanctuaries are found in Jerusalem.
Believers here follow the path of suffering or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the church of the grave on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
It is here, according to the Christian view, that the navel of the world symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem is located in the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the Lamentation Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in A.D. 70.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes there with wishes that then come true.
Take a trip up high
The ruins of the fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies, which Herod the Great had built for his family in A.D. 25.
They lie on a rock wall in the mountains at a height of 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
All others bring a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters there is the famous Hermon ski resort, which attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometres.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods were said to have lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There are preserved ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean desert, as well as approximately 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There the collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso will be exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures by the visitors and bath attendants of the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the memorial to the children, which was built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
Upon entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the lands in which they died resound.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing Something for Health
Israel’s three main recreational areas lie on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three locations there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salinity and thus even carries non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and medicinal mud as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of stressed nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets are hidden in the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia ran through this city.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved here the beautiful Andromeda, with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets, which are named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortuna is said to be hold by all who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo events.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Today evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Tourist watchlist
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the journey is better taken in no euros, but in dollars, which can simply be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a expressway line and in Haifa the only underground line of the country with six stations that connects the Unterstadt with the Oberstadt.
Actually, it's an underground funicular.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which is enough including changing for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is resting.
And on Sunday morning, the workweek begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, marine products, fish without scales and food containing both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice of different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
There are many well-fed cats that roam through the streets comfortably and unmolested.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don't say no to treats.
A rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional 15 dollars a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the visa requirement was lifted on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MEPs and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already acting with fake certificates
Every year 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families remaining in their home country.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to pass a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail trade.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
Not only language tests, but also tests must be put into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for the receipt and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also excluded from this law are persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
The whole of the examination places will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative for the introduction of the tests was supported by the representatives of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law came into force in the press: What does the whole thing actually bring?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring to the Russians as well as to the migrant workers?
In particular, spokesmen of the Migration Authority replied, the aim was to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelev, Head of the Representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected before they leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical examination encounter problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who, under the pretext of helping him, put him in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure without food and documents with dozens of his like months and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
Many complaints from our migrants reach us.
"In your home country you will be promised one thing, and on arrival you will be cheated, your passports will be taken and you will not receive the promised salary," confirms Tolib Schwaripov, Head of the Labour Migration Department of the Tajik Migration Authority.
Don't scold me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to earn their money in Russia, admit that they are not only unable to speak the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: only a few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school clothes.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect with regard to the law.
Only migrants with legal status must take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of migrant workers continue to reside illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Prohibited entry for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain an official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
Russian police personnel know that most of our documents are faked and we are not registered, and then there are cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," Tajike Umed Hushkadamov says to journalists.
"Just don't shy away from the cost of false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be falsified.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by federal migration authorities.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive it for nothing: every migrant who hoped to be able to save himself so tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights activists agree that the main immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that certificates cannot be bought easily.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time that they will have time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered jobs in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Ministry of Interior ignores illegal arms market
The proportion of legal weapons in crime is extremely low
The Russian Interior Ministry is planning to tighten the arms law for private arms owners.
The authorities are reacting to recent events: injured in wedding shootings and seven dead in the amok run of Moscow lawyer Dmitri Winogradov.
The police want to ban the use of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age of possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the Chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarovaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act would soon be submitted to the Duma.
Not all are satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various arms associations - ask the authorities to refrain from "senseless tightening".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal justice officer, Vasiliy Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the Ministry of the Interior statistics, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in 2012 over six months, while a total of 1,168 thousand were committed for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private arms owners will not prevent criminals from using themselves on the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors, you can find any weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranez.
On the second channel are illegal weapons, which are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen both from the police's arms chambers and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
Many military camps often experienced explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, weapons manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that do not stand up to international competition and therefore squander arms under the hand on the black market, for example in Moscow," reports the expert.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries like Kyrgyzstan.
"There is its own, sometimes artisanal production, as well as a mafia that organizes smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Public Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Criminological Literature and publicly available data on portals on weapons.
According to the investigators, most of the illegal weapons come from the army and legal protection authorities.
Half of all weapons on the black market were there because of the "guilt of those responsible for their work with weapons," the report says.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict areas, 14% come from thefts in the production of weapons, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun store, who does not want to be named, assures that weapons found during illegal excavations have long since been bought by no one, because they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get supplies in a weapons warehouse.
A gun, such as a TT-type gun, is bought by an ensign.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"Of course, the police know everything and therefore, if they cannot comply with the crime detection plan, they periodically make control purchases from traders who offer illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
"Like in a luxury store"
Buyers and sellers most often find each other through acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone became aware of me and suggested to come to the "Begovaya" station, where a person would wait for me to take me to a certain place where we could negotiate the price.
The price of the gun I only learned there
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need an acquaintance who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such an acquaintance, but I don't trust him."
There are traders in the markets, but there you have to go and arrange with a code like "of Ivan Ivanovich, who lets tell that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I'm actually coming to some rings right now about a friend I trust.
He also gives me the rings because he knows I don't rat him out.
Newbies are looking for weapons in different ways.
