No one can yet predict whether the protests will swell further or whether they will soon run out of air.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organizations.
In addition to raising the modest wages of simple Walmart and fast-food workers, the organizers of the protests are pursuing the goal of establishing trade unions.
So far, this sector of the economy has hardly been organized by trade unions.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called Black Friday, where sales took place in the USA, attracting millions of customers, which sometimes led to crowds of hands.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, laid down their jobs and, together with trade unions and left-wing activists, struck branches of the chain whose target group is low and middle income.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in the Walmart stores are, on average, between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
Therefore, many of the low-paid Walmart employees buy only at their own workplace.
The prices and product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the USA.
According to critics, Walmart can often sell the goods so cheaply only because the employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, for example missing forklift trucks or hand scanners.
The participants of the Black Friday protests demanded wage increases and expressed their anger at the fact that the contribution to the company's own health insurance had risen from 30 to 100 dollars a month.
A typical Walmart employee, who earns 9.5 US dollars an hour, could not afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from California University in Berkeley have shown that if the company raises the average salary to $12 an hour, it would cost Walmart $32 billion.
That's about 1.1% more than they're now donating for pay.
If Walmart completely transferred the wage increases to customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
For them this would be an increase of only $12.39 per year compared to today.
Proponents of Walmart are pleased to note that only nine states were protesting and that they did not cause any loss to the company.
The Black Friday lasted the next day in its shop from 8 o'clock in the evening on Thursday to midnight, and during this period Walmart sold about 5000 items per second.
In total, the Walmart-Kassen carried out almost 100 million transactions on "Black Friday".
In an interview on the website of the left-wing Huffington Post, the company's spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed that a total of "less than five" Walmart employees laid down the work and that the protest action was only "an additional PR trick" of the union that organized the protests.
"Free cash register!"
The protests continued this week in New York, but their destination was not Walmart stores (which are not wanted in this progressive city and are therefore so far nonexistent), but McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald's says the company is selling billions of portions, and yet you're not given sick days, and you're not paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, member of the New York City Council
