"The brain is only moderately outsmarted so far"
The theme of expanded reality, popular among followers of modern technologies, has been commonly perceived by the lens of a special eyeglass.
First Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it became known that Microsoft had also applied for a patent.
In conversation with the head of the interactive 3D technology group at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, however, it becomes clear that the glasses were only a transit station for the company's scientists.
It excites the possibility of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but we want to expand the limits of this interaction.
So far, mankind has largely been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to anticipate 5-10 years and anticipate the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are progressing, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else awaits us in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, a lot of things still play out on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system gets more data) could be improved, the output not yet decisive.
We try to change this, work on real three-dimensional display systems based on various technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could complement the real world much more easily with virtual objects.
And first of all, we should get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
She's popular, but isn't she overrated?
- I'm sure it's not the all-purpose solution, because it raises questions about privacy, because you don't always want to inform everyone by about your actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and scarce gestures instead of sweeping gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gestures and language.
- How so?
We'd like you to ask me to give you this bubble can, for example?
They say it and point to it at the same time.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and can't afford at the time?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work primarily on the development of new types of sensors that allow us to capture reactions from people more precisely.
These can be laser sensors, for example, because they offer a good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- What demands do you place on modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or anything else?
- The present generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixel itself, but the quality of the matrix and depth.
Seen in this way, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of algorithms have more work to do.
Not only the resolution along the X- and Y-, but also along the Z-axis must be taken into account.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
Man's movements are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps are too little, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our Redmond laboratory with a adjustable processing delay of between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today's commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how this affects the interaction of man and machine.
For my work, I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras might solve the problem...
Or increase the problem as more calculations would be needed.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system in which we could play with different camera angles to see how this helps us to determine a position three-dimensionally.
- If I remember correctly, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that with regard to the application of advanced reality technology in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in your uplifted hand on the road, but I think the greatest option would be a "changing" expanded reality, in which we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and in this lies their strength (private things can only you see), but at the same time their weakness, because an extended reality by means of glasses prevents you from working together with others on virtual objects.
Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is not only accessible to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point to: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often talk about the fact that expanded reality represents the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection pad.
She's very sensitive to pressure!
But there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the "images in the air" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is at the moment as weak as someone blowing over the ball of hands.
There are also wristbands that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, which is also a potential direction.
- Have you tried to outwit the brain?
Make it think it feels what it should feel when it sees something right now?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried yet.
Here is another task that we will have to deal with for a long time to come, namely to let a person who is physically in a closed room believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms as well as large balls.
So far, the brain is only moderately outsmarted, and we still have many busy years ahead of us.
This is what makes the work in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: We are only at the beginning of many topics.
