Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth dwellers on board are searching for a replacement planet.
In order to save mankind, the important question arises as to how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the replacement planet?
I do not think there are many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least inhabit hypothetically.
"Mars and Venus," says the scientific assistant of the Astronomical Starberg Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, the surface of Venus has a temperature of 500 degrees.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first addressed the question of reproduction in space in terms of flora.
Experiments with plants were carried out half a century earlier.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit did not differ in the least from earthly species.
It followed the breeding of insects, more precisely tiny fruit flies (drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent to space to investigate how weightlessness affects the development of embryos.
A normal chick is developing.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick must find a hold; it must be able to stand on its legs and begin to move," explains Vladimir Sychev, laboratory director of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN.
Without solid ground, the chicks turned wild.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely dulled.
The chicks did not react to light and sounds.
Four days later, they just died.
"Two times we let chicks slip and then set the whole thing up because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychev notes to the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be present on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized and sent into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"That was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats were given offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
In contrast to animals, man could do so in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered this question," says space veteran Wachtang Wachnadse.
In June 1964, just a year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andriyan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawizkaja, who was twice in orbit and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Still, there's still a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts, where after long flights everything went well and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even on flights to orbit," concludes Kosmonaut Waleri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
Yet mankind must seek new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and artificial gravity.
The hydrolaboratory in the cosmonaut preparation centre is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
The water represents the weightlessness.
Even if adults find water to be pleasant, it is a strange environment; but infants feel water to be a natural element.
It's like the little Ichtyanders testifying that life on the land descended from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the mother's belly for about 9 months in the amniotic fluid, and the fact that it can become more accustomed to water.
In principle, this is logical, since only 2 weeks pass from birth to the first swim.
"This is not enough time to forget something," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
Thus, while weightlessness is a much more natural condition for a newborn child, the woman cannot do without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles regress tremendously quickly and thus also diminish the ability to push out the child.
All right, let's get around this with birth-seeking aids.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to push the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valeri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the gravity, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put in orbit like an adult for training in a load suit.
He will simply lack what is of fundamental importance for his life.
"This experiment, which we are undertaking together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled person, a completely inappropriate person," says the head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Igor Pestow.
So far, the birth of children in outer space is mere theory.
At some point, however, it becomes a reality when the Earth's inhabitants in their spaceships set out to become a distant planet that will be the home for their descendants born in space.
