At the meeting of the Chamber of Deputies' Control Committee, you spoke about a joint Czech-German project in which the laws of both countries concerning public contracts were compared.
What was it specifically about?
This is a parallel test that we started about two years ago.
To put it simply, it is a question of the European legislature defining how public contracts should be managed, on which national legislation is based, and finally, the actual practical application.
We have compared all this with each other, and although the examination has not yet been completed, we have found very interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws are perhaps even more "stricter and more perfect" for us, but the actual application in Germany is better in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to set up new and more precise rules over and over again. It is also necessary to deal with the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What results from this project for you?
It is precisely this kind of joint control that could help us stop constantly trying to perfect the laws and reduce and balance thresholds if this appears to be not particularly positive.
Economic efficiency means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But the reduction of thresholds for contracts does not guarantee that we will achieve this goal.
Perhaps it is even the case that in this way we only burden the system with excessive "paper stuff" and those who seek gaps in the system have made it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
