Do you see the adoption of this law rather positive, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be complied with.
Under the previous rules, persons subject to scrutiny are already accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to the effect that any failure to comply with the Act on Procurement is a violation of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I do not think that way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system and not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making process.
Such a system only puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out of here?
First of all, let us say which path is not effective.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system now prohibited or allowed?
After all, a law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then the head of government cannot simply come, and the supervisory authority, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, can hinder its activity.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he can't say that we act as if nothing were.
The Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and this is also correct for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, however, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best bid is excluded due to formal errors alone.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied properly - and that is what I believe is missing from us.
