Šimon Ornest: We want to collect positive energy at our concerts
What do you think will happen in less than a month of the end of the world?
This is one of those disaster reports that we people like to jump to.
With our band The Tap Tap we make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It's a nationwide charity event that we've been planning for two years.
For this we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, whose end is predicted for December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 21:00.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be about the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone 12 hours ahead of us.
Who gave this idea?
Originally from me, after that we designed the idea together with our graphic artist Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to collect enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we give this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and keychains against the end of the world, with which the people can also support us through www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap, together with other performers, has also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world with the title "The end of the world is falling out".
Even today, the anthem on YouTube is very popular. Will it also be heard at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and that the end of the world does not take place...
The anthem is to be sung simultaneously by all performers at all three concerts.
In addition, the hymns will be broadcast live together on a direct line from Czech television.
The text of the anthem was written by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, and Xindl X also sings with...
How did you come to work with both of them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many charity events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us, and have fun with it.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the accessible education centre Studeo, on which we have been working for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, we will build our own building in which we will move into with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
What criteria did you choose?
We wanted to put together a program that appeals to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere perform with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.
Find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "large events" also planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and we will also prepare an interesting programme with interesting guests for this concert.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would also like to combine this with appearances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already appeared in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs have to be carried in the luggage compartment. We also have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked out without problems so far, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad, you have a comparison of the situation in individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than ours, we have witnessed in Russia that everything in the East is still in its infancy.
Opposite Prague Moscow is absolutely not disabled. It is still unusual there if someone in a wheelchair is travelling alone in the city center.
It is not even a matter of course there that you leave a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that are trying to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way must we catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still a lot of things we hang out with...
However, it should be noted that improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to be able to move independently in public space, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not exactly common for a larger group of disabled people to participate actively in social events there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Public respect and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only isolated cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intense.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone, among other things, I founded a music association together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our presenter, L’A Angelovič, has used to say, something has gotten out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us, and we have also begun to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if one does something and this cannot be seen outwardly, one's performance does not exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good lecturers, high-quality equipment and the like.
Was it your goal to get this far with The Tap Tap?
From the very beginning, I felt the potential that things can be handled differently.
In show business, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are only a few really unique things, and I dare to claim that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression the viewer usually has is of course pity; this is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live a full life and develop if they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is not just progress for them, but for the whole of society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you cannot compromise on many things and you also have to demand a certain discipline.
However, I believe that this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic performances, and when they find that they have rehearsals twice a week, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, the enthusiasm of many quickly disappears.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: L’A Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go.
Anyone who has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
