The MVRDV architects prove that the true adventures are not only in mind - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large business, says: "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder what we still need a library for today.
Everyone has Internet, iPad and e-books.
No one's going to one of those old-style libraries today, is it?
Spijkenisse, a sleep city that is hardly in need of a visit at the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant community has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands as a whole.
In order to counter this stupid circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro notes as beautifully pinned reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers recognized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library must be here!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural office MVRDV, master of the brash bar charts and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with familiar serenity and appeared to the competition hearing anno 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin in his face.
And while the jury was still looking around and twitching with the armpits, the cheeky Maas piled up his exquisite souvenirs in size to a pyramid and ended his action-based speech with the words: "Dear city community!"
So this is him, my proposal for the Buchenberg of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is piled up.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This makes the faceless small town retreat, which has so far had no more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunned ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
But above all Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
First impression: Bookeldorado under cheese bell.
There is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the real pleasures of reading and space are opened up when climbing the topography within walking distance.
The all around glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lights clearly speak the language of a public city square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
And books, books, books everywhere.
"Normally, the bookshelfs stand along the façade, and in the middle lies a large, dark room, which is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and put the reading area inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: in the middle there are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental centre and building technology centre.
A special joy are the black bookcases, which are sometimes wall covering, sometimes parapets, sometimes staircase railings.
Optics, haptics and smell are foreign.
Even die-hard architects and civil engineers shake the head of the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycling materials here," explains Joop Troublerst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, on request of the standard.
And so one day we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
For many years in the Netherlands a mm-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root base in greenhouses and on fields.
That's cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece was pressed - for the first time in these quantities - into four centimeters thick plates.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-capable material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like a sports shoe.
After 105 steps you have reached the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-meter-long hike, the Literaturcafé is rewarded not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and stuffed ficus trees.
They provide the atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literature mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled with geothermal energy.
Although the Buchenberg stands under a glass fall, the sun shines only briefly inside even on sunny days.
The wide wooden glue binders, which stand across the glass façade, serve as shading and capture a large part of the solar radiation.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls the Boekenberg Spijkenisses "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, every resident was invited to donate a book from his personal holdings.
For the time being, the optical gaps in the library, which is not yet fully stocked, - currently 70,000 pieces - are to be filled.
The concept has worked out.
The shelves are filled up to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
And if it's just an ornament.
With this MVRDV has succeeded the royal discipline, which is called the identity foundation in the specialist jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert in US-European relations, Berlin balances on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy, away from a policy managed, so to speak, by the US, towards a German foreign policy.
It is also difficult to see that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still touching on their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy like France or Great Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to push the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That definitely matters.
But I wouldn't want to give it too much weight either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps it will even give Germany some respect.
After all, it signals that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be considered.
There are different opinions on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly declared itself in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic politics, these differences have always existed.
I believe that Obama’s government has a secret understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu's politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not currently the case.
So they can't be part of a broader line, and instead, they have to push things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of the relationship with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I believe that the Germans are aware that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player - does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or does Germany still have a difficult leadership role?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, if we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany takes on a larger role, various anti-German feelings become free.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the USA.
It must be receptive to various neighbours and opinions and that is not easy.
Now the influence of the US in European politics is steadily diminishing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, who else is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, they are uncomfortable and make it much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together on the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
