The aim, however, was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the president's bond and take over the leadership of the nation.
He's facing a complex task.
Mexico has been able to prove itself economically well under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
"My government is committed to reducing violence," Pena Nieto told US President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this objective.
Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico before joining the US President on an equal footing.
In this densely populated, extensive part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are shared.
A direct man
In the remote town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember him.
Inhabitants of the holiday resort attribute to him the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, one can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto built and which represent a great improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
