The Procuratorate claims that Bradley Manning did not complain about mistreatment
The prosecutor's office contradicts Bradley Manning's accusations that he was mistreated in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks to dismiss the charges due to harsh prison conditions
Private of the U.S. Army is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
The prosecutor's office tried to find out on Friday that the army-liberated Bradley Manning - accused of the greatest disclosure of confidential information in US history - missed several occasions to complain about the allegedly suffered abuse in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Mannings during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein explained that documents relating to weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month term in Quantico, Virginia did not have any complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a defence request to dismiss the prosecution - Manning had already been adequately punished by the hard time in prison - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The US Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In the Friday hearing, Fein went through with Manning the forms that officers had filled out after their meeting with Manning during his detention in Quantico Military Prison, where he had been serving from July 2010 to April 2011 under increased prison conditions.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards to be "excellent" and the treatment by the institution as a whole to be "very professional".
According to Fein, the forms did not contain any complaints about abuse, although officers had asked Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they had to deal with them, but that they had not been recorded.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) "No problems," and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," says Manning.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to examine the suicidal thoughts he mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to downgrade his observation status to "prevention of injuries".
The military declared that it had assigned this restrictive status - one stage below the risk of suicide - to its protection and to the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and to get rid of the observation status to prevent injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," said Manning.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marine Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said that in Kuwait he had considered suicide and had become unconscious because of the heat.
Not knowing what was going on with him or in the outside world was stressful.
"My world shrunk on Camp Arafjon, on this cage," said Manning on Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
He was only allowed one mattress, one blanket, flip flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he had tried to keep moving, because it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards couldn't see his face anymore, he was woken up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas Military Prison.
On Friday, Judge Manning also asked about an accusation he had raised in his statement on Thursday - so he had to sleep one night naked in his cell in Quantico and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had stated that during this census he had never had the opportunity to wrap himself up with his blanket.
During the interview on Friday, Manning stated that he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he was forced to sleep naked the night before. He had previously tried to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning had told the officer that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his prison experiences and drastically reduce his prison sentence if he is convicted at his trial in the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will plead lesser offenses for guilty, while other charges, which are considered too extreme, are to be challenged.
The hearing is scheduled to continue for this weekend and the prosecution is expected to justify the detention conditions.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the rules applicable to all the highest security precautions in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favouring the enemy, unlawful publication of intelligence on the Internet, transmission of national defence information and theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he is threatened with life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to accuse the emigrants - they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes that Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when perplexity spread within me.
