Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is in love with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that even Israel and the United States cannot push out.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
Militaryly, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome," has proved its worth and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
For at least a while Israel will be able to sleep calmer.
In diplomatic terms, the United States remains steadfast in its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has been doing well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free from suicide bombers - not least thanks to the blocking facilities that are being built into the West Bank and thus into the bulk of a possible Palestinian state. However, these protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared to be illegal under international law, but are being further developed.
In the run-up to the January 22 elections, his Likud party, led by Avigdor Lieberman, joined an even more militant group.
Why do these deceitful Palestinians also coddle and leave their own state to them?
If they actually had control over the West Bank, would they not fire rockets just like their fellow Gazans?
No, it's better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
