Even if the Islamists, now in power in Egypt and in other countries, have little left for Israel, they will first focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel's defence budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbours together.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to repair their economies.
The fact that pragmatic President Morsi and Barack Obama joined forces to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign - and perhaps symbolise the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking tentative steps towards democratisation, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination - a powder keg that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Suppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and the growth of the Arab population will only exacerbate this situation.
Bloody missions to repress Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly take their diplomatic toll over the years.
