The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health if they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by extracting sulfur from the volcano Kawah Ijen in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
For this purpose, it must descend every day to the ground of its crater, where the sulphurous gas emanating from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the steep paths of stone.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb at the pace of the turtle, keeping their balance and carefully taking their steps so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell years ago on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen.
The mine workers of Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for each kilo of sulphur they mine.
Arriving at the top, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the volcanic deposits since 1960 and (never better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocents) for each kilo of sulphur.
This is then sold to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocents) each, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each way," explains Anto, who usually makes three distances a day.
For each track he needs three hours, after which he is completely done, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
But what looks like a miserable reward for such an almost inhuman effort is three times what he would earn with field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid per day at the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not as hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, for a reason as important as sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I took her to Java to convert her to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
27-year-old Anto has been putting his life at risk at Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already left him the first traces, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'm going to work here for two more years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than just acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent, but life-punished young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a carrier.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other beams and gets up every morning at two o'clock, because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluishly in the darkness.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
About 400 carriers load the baskets with sulphur on their shoulders on the crater floor.
Despite their large profits, the mining company has not mechanised sulphur mining to save costs and does not supply any equipment to those who work on their own account and are paid for by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) per camera, which the guardians of this nature park together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) require from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human gurney.
"This work is for animals and not for humans," says Madrusin, a sturdy 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as possible" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even if the sulfur burns the throat and the eyes itch, when the wind suddenly turns and the miners are trapped in the thick columns rising from the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains about serious diseases ... of course except the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have deformed from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik with his 53 years is only able to carry 50 kg.
Every day he and his companions break 15 tons of sulphur out of the volcano, which are transported by three trucks over a goat path between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari at a distance of 18 kilometers.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life," Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, with some teeth missing.
Of his five children, the oldest also works as a sulfur carrier at the age of 30.
Time passes, but poorness keeps generation to generation in one of the hardest professions in the world: those who work as human vices at Kawah Ijen.
