We are the worst in the world when it comes to planting, so we realized that it was a subject that we had to take care of.
We knew that the government had tried a lot, such as marketing perfume with pheromones or organizing speed dating evenings (fast flirts).
It is possible that many of these ideas were creative, but they did not necessarily lead to success.
So we thought, why don't we make something as creative as possible to address this problem, such as composing a rap?
1.2 Children
Those who do not take this issue lightly are the government of Singapore.
Every year, it spends $1,300 on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for couples and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has had little success so far.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its National Population Authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was over 2 - which is also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't the Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy of the National Population Authority, says this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities".
"This has made it possible for people to have much more options in terms of life goals and priorities besides getting married and forming a family," she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the higher number of singles and to the delaying of marriage and births, the result of which is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in immigration in order to counteract the reduction of the population led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore there are websites where the barely concealed xenophobia against many new immigrants is flourishing, especially against the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the Singapore governing party achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known impact on a nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs, and immigration policies, the Singapore example also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to ensure that not so many small apartments are built.
It has already had an impact on the housing market.
The Department of Urban Development has begun to monitor the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the single person's lifestyle and that they deter construction companies from building large homes for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out by days and even weeks faster than the larger units.
This means that they are much better for our cash flow.
He admits, however, that the new standards provide clearer orientations for developers who have previously been put in the way of obstacles if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, the talks with Singaporeans working in the financial district show that they will not have much impact.
"People are stressed out, the apartments and the education are expensive, which is why it is pushed out by many," says a young manager.
The children can have others.
"It is important for me to have my own money and time," says another man, about twenty years old.
Men and women cite their careers, the stress and the cost of property and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
That is why the Singaporeans have the last word when it comes to having children - there is still so much the government can do.
The offline private offline is online private
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "the area of private life where one is entitled to protection from any kind of interference".
What is private for someone under the age of 16?
How is this definition applied to his everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he exposes himself to when making known on the Internet situations that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15 who are often on the Internet.
In four of the cases, they linked the term to "something very personal" on a personal level and "to the password and the user" when they applied it to the social networks.
"I wouldn't reveal my deepest secrets in a post," says 10-year-old Jorge while trying to explain the meaning of "private" in websites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I'm also spending my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that isn't mine, or someone who makes the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, nudes, crimes, or to write abusive or violent comments.
Jorge assures us that he knows 35 friends he has in FB and nine in Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up on Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone will answer me, I'm just uploading them," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can talk quickly to relatives in the distance or with friends," he says.
Asked, he answers that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown person.
Even if someone would recommend a stranger to him, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask he admits not to know 20 of the people he added to his friend list.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, for example music," he says.
According to the boy, no one suggested or asked him for his address or telephone number.
"If someone pushes me or demands it from me, I simply remove it from my account," he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unknown to experiences known today as cyberbullying.
A friend's friend was blackmailed in a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim didn't close the account.
"He just did it privately."
He then explains a number of steps to securely configure a user account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I'd do that if I didn't like him or if I wanted to wipe him out.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English with a university degree in education and learning, believes that in order to orient the children and young people, it must be understood that it is the purpose of social networks to inform.
"The Internet was created as a medium for the search for information, but with the appearance of these pages the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that the academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master's degree in pedagogy at Yale University and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants", shaped these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who are supposed to teach them, when we are still learning ourselves," he says.
He explains that this is a complex issue, "because we require them to have a defined criterion on what can be disseminated, published or said, at an age where maturity is not sufficient."
"They should also be selective when it is most important to them to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and young people what privacy is to ask them questions that make them think.
"To tell them not to do it doesn't work," he says.
Porras then mentions some possibilities: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger. Then why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like to have a photo of you published, like the one you published from a friend?
Do you know what the others are publishing about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission before when you labeled photos of parties?
And one more question: Do everyone need to know what you're doing at every moment?
Another point is to give them understanding that they need to act online as they do offline.
They're the same rules.
"Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks," he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educator consultant, comments that it is essential that parents carefully read the guidelines of social networks.
When they understand all sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children need to be reminded of the lesson "You must not speak to strangers".
Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was to be signed theoretically by the seven present governments.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasur. Sources in the State and President Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the retreat, but then stated that it would be published on the Peruvian Government's website at some time.
On questions relating to the text, they stated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the image of the president's meeting without sound was broadcast in the press room with the message "private meeting, limited audio".
The few information circulating among journalists was received from the press officers of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
After that, the presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the Humala Declaration and not the official document at the conclusion of the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and the so-called Lima Declaration, previously announced, was also not published on this occasion, despite the press's strong request.
On the official website of the ASPA, you can convince yourself that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems for journalists were in place, but to a large extent they restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague which resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which will begin on Monday in The Hague, in the trial that Lima initiated against Santiago, to listen to the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are currently presenting to this international court," said Humala along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and remains a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts," adds Piñera and greeted Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
Both presidents confirmed that they would submit to the ICJ after Colombia had brought an action against the Bogotá Agreement following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered to be a serious mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this International Court of Justice.
The summit was attended by the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011, after the resignation of its President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The head of state read the final document stating that 16 decisions were taken and that the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for a total investment of 17 billion dollars.
Regarding the decisions taken, he said that the Unasur countries "will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we will extend the decisions on residence rights."
He said that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised cross-border crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take a triumphant course, but should serve to expand our output and show our peoples a better future," added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial links in South America and especially in rural and border areas...and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms," said the Peruvian president in a read-out statement.
Among these projects would be five Peruvians who would be on the cross-axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which would provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace, with good neighbourly relations, was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that on Saturday in Mexico he expected a meeting with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, in order to treat respectfully the maritime conflict after a judgment of the ICC called into question by Bogotá.
"Maybe I will meet President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)", Santos said.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also requires talks with Nicaragua," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectfully as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the new President of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the Summit, the Defence Ministers of the 2013 Plan of Action Block also met in advance to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, even if the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru presides at the time of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn to integrate its citizens," says Rafael Correa
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, today confirmed that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal whereby "South America can actually learn something from Europe."
Correa, who attended the 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which took place in Lima, told state television in Peru that Europeans "died themselves in the Second World War and in other conflicts" and that "today are practically a fatherland."
