Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto against Paraguay in the Unasur at least until his next elections, arguing that the organism "must remain hard and not allow any opportunistism and no coup d'état disguised as legal" because it "destructed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay."
Moreover, the President of Ecuador considers the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, now and after the judgment of the International Court of Justice of The Hague, which favored the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua to negotiate the maritime borders between the two countries with Nicaragua "absolutely justified".
At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South American and a Central American state.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in pursuit of a common path.
They must be comprehensively dealt with so that they can be overcome and looked forward.
He also trusted a good conclusion to the disputes over the maritime borders between Peru and Chile before the same court, saying that "it is right for Latin America to call international authorities if both countries commit to accept the verdict, even if it is very harsh."
With regard to the possibility that he would stand as a candidate for the next presidential election in Ecuador in order to achieve his third consecutive mandate, he stated that he saw this possibility "with a lot of optimism and joy, although sometimes it is also very difficult."
Correa assured that if he lost the elections in February 2013, he would withdraw from political life.
Power has never interested me personally, but under such unfair circumstances as Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement had the belief that it was I who guaranteed this probable victory, so I have to shoulder this responsibility," he said.
If I were to win, it would be my last period as president, and then I retire from public life.
This also applies if we lose.
"That's decided," he explained.
Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of the President of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, in Cuba.
I have just spoken to the Vice-President of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro, who told me that he travelled there for a planned, routine treatment and that he would be expected to be able to travel to Cuba again after the election campaign.
"In no case does it mean a relapse in the state of health of President Chávez," he commented.
