Cause of death due to AIDS is a late detection today
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed with the results: HIV-positive.
"It was as if a bomb struck," he says about the moment when he received the diagnosis that the doctor tried "to weaken" without any apparent success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inform himself about it, and this with such commitment that he was celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), in which he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine in the early 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At that time, even the director of a clinic at the IMSS avoided saying goodbye "because it led to a dead end."
Back then, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome even with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic, who know nothing about their disease and where the virus has already caused damage and exhausted their immune system, and who are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after AIDS appeared in the world, i.e. after the first cases reported, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient taking up treatment in time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of HCG HIV Unit, who said that this information was supported by a prestigious scientific publication in April this year.
Andrade Villanueva, a specialist in infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, commented that, since 2008, scientists concluded that although AIDS was not a death sentence, the years of survival and quality of life depended on the degree of impairment of the immune system at the start of treatment, and that those who are not addicted to drugs would have greater chances: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above statements mean that those who receive the diagnosis HIV-positive at the age of 25, in this sense, "can easily become 75 years old as long as they are under control," said this expert.
In order to be able to correctly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is on average 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA Annual Report), it is true that 60 percent of patients registered in the national database have died since AIDS was released.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by May of this year 187 deaths have occurred; however, it is assured that universal access to antiretroviral medicines has been available since 2005.
So why do people still die from it?
- I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years we have had no supply problems with the drugs. The problem is that people come in a very advanced state because they do not know their infection state, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. In order to be able to influence global mortality, more early diagnoses are required, which is why all persons who require this must be offered massive detection tests."
This proposal is approved by the experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (National Committee on AIDS Prevention in Jalisco) and also by the patients such as Fabrizio, who had his test performed at a private laboratory, for the only reason that it had been made by a friend of his who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had Kaposi's sarcoma (a cancer-like tumor), which is one of the usual complications.
Everything is different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die and don't want to hear anything.
"If I already have to die, I prefer to burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was to improve, I nourish myself well, exercise and take the medications.
All his parents know today is that he had cancer.
I live a normal life like everyone else.
"I work, do a lot, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," Fabrizio noted, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO in order to animate with his testimony those who are afraid today in the context of the global AIDS Day.
They should take the test if they belong to the risk group. The sooner they know if they are HIV-positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between the health programs and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, journalist from Guadalajara, who has taken up the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the designated places, "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; they were handed over individually earlier, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who have no access to a condom," he said.
Adolescents are at risk for new infections.
"What do you need it for?" is a common mockery of social workers, orientation staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and in the health system that young people do not want to expose themselves to, the correspondent assured.
He suggested reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should be located not only behind the counter, but in output devices in public toilets of facilities frequented by young people.
Promiscuity should not be promoted.
They should not be paid the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied to the question of whether preservatives would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality does not look like this; it is best to bring the condoms closer to those who already engage in sexual activity," he put it to the point.
Key Data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
Nationally, the state is fourth in new and cumulated cases of AIDS, and thirteen in HIV.
92% of contagion cases are via sexual intercourse, 6% via blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because there are 4 or 5 people who do not know it in each case.
After the United States Court of Appeal has confirmed a judgment that does not recognise the restructuring of the liabilities of the Vitro Group, achieved through a trade agreement in Mexico, an ominous precedent is created for any national company with subsidiaries in the neighbouring country that has payment problems.
So it could be said that the procedures for the survival of the companies that allow Mexican laws are not valid in the country of the stars and stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the recognition of the judgment by Judge Harlin Hale at the Bancarrotas Court on 15 June for the northern district of Texas means that Mexican companies are helplessly exposed to seizure of their property beyond the river Bravo.
However, the decision opens the door to the largest glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the Supreme Court of the United States for three inconsistencies.
While the judge of the case points out that creditors must be subject to the bankruptcy law of the United States, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeal, based in New Orleans, first states that the main proceedings are the trade negotiations in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings for companies with a cross-border profile is not known.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created for this purpose, using the American Law Institute as a mediator.
Secondly, the judgment states that without the votes of the companies, after recognition of the debts in the bankruptcy fund which Vitro’s branches had with their parent company, the necessary majority for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been achieved.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican laws.
In fact, Vitro is not the first case in which this scheme has been approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities were confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles (Federal Institute for Trade Concurrencies) among the Group's companies.
It is also true that after the withdrawal of the votes of the branches, the creditors of Vitro, the creditors who complained to the courts of the United States against Vitro, i.e. the vulture funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have reached a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent against 37 percent.
This is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro is responsible for its difficult situation from 2008 in the context of the major economic crisis in the United States, which struck the country.
For this reason, the González Sada family objects to the same court of appeal so that the vote can be held in plenary, i.e. by all judges, because only three of them voted.
If this is not allowed, the Cerciorare objection is filed, which requires the review of the proceedings by a higher authority, in this case by the Supreme Court of the United States.
The serious thing about this case is that the court left aside a document sent by the Mexican government under the Figura amicus curiae (Friend of the Court) describing the proceedings conducted by Vitro under the Trade Concurrence Act and pointing out that it had strictly adhered to the agreements signed by both countries in order to comply with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
It is also noted that the country has been subject to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the established rules for cases of cross-border insolvency, which guarantee the equality of debtors and creditors.
Two-banded carambole: a blow for Vitro and for the country.
